[1] Paraguay
Date: January 30, 2006
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: ABC Digital, Asuncion, Paraguay. 30 Jan 2006, [trans. JGM; edited]
<http://www.abc.com.py/articulos.php?fec=2006-01-30&pid=231372&sec=3>

Professionals from the Public Health Ministry recommend the community
to eliminate mosquito breeding sites that accumulate after every
rainfall, in order to prevent the occurrence of dengue fever cases
transmitted by _Aedes aegypti_.
According to data from the Department of Entomology of the National
Service for Malaria Eradication (SENEPA, according to its Spanish
initials), the _Aedes aegypti_ larval infestation index in some
Asuncion areas is on average 4.1 percent.
The areas considered to be at risk and with the highest larvae
infestation indexes are as follows: Panambi Vera, Los Laureles, San
Pablo, and Hipodromo, with the following values: household index 22.4
percent; Breteau index 2.9 percent, and (water) recipient index 5.3 percent.
The likelihood of dengue fever virus transmission is reduced when the
aforementioned indexes are less than1 percent. This situation may be
reproduced in some other areas of the country. Consequently, it is
important to increase surveillance and to establish corrective
actions with the participation of the community as a whole.
Vector surveillance is of paramount importance in the fight against
dengue fever. Of all strategies, the most effective one is the
elimination of mosquito breeding sites.
It is important to mention that after rainfalls and with high
humidity levels, household surveillance and appropriate cleaning are
mandatory in order to prevent increases in mosquito infestation in
the community.
Dengue fever is a viral disease transmitted by a mosquito called
_Aedes aegypti_. There are basically 2 types of dengue fever: classic
dengue fever and hemorrhagic dengue fever. Generally, when the
mosquito transmits the infection [to a patient] for the very first
time, it [causes] a case of classic dengue fever. When a 2nd
transmission occurs [in the same patient], there is a higher risk for
acquiring hemorrhagic dengue fever, which is a much more severe form
of the disease and may be fatal.
Symptoms of the disease include: high fever, intense headache, severe
eye, bone, and joint pain, and skin rash. These symptoms occur 3 to 7
days after being bitten by an infected mosquito. With the
aforementioned symptoms, it is recommended that the person not
self-medicate, and he/she must go immediately to a health center
and/or physician.
It is recommended to inform the community about the following:
1. Inspect yards at least 2 times per week, with special emphasis on
the detection and elimination of mosquito breeding sites.
2. Put sand in vases, and keep water reservoirs closed.
3. Dispose of used tires in covered places, or fill them with soil,
in order to prevent water accumulation inside them.
4. Go immediately to a health center if a person has fever and
headache without mucus elimination [?]; this warrants action, if
possible, within 24 hours.
5. Immediately report suspected cases of dengue fever to health
services, so that epidemiological investigation is on time and effective.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[_Aedes aegypti_] is the most important and widespread vector of
dengue and dengue hemorrhagic fever. This day-biting mosquito
breeds in a variety of man-made container habitats (e.g. domestic
water pots, discarded tires, empty tin cans) and also in some areas
in natural container-type habitats such as tree holes and rock pools.
It has become a peridomestic mosquito.
Risks of dengue outbreaks are often assessed, at least in part, using
larval indices. Several such indices are employed to estimate the
abundance of _Ae. aegypti_ breeding in an area. The most commonly
used is the house (= premise) index, which is the percentage of
houses, including surrounding compounds, that have _aegypti_ larvae
in some of their containers. Other indices are the container (=
receptacle) index, the percentage of water-holding containers
examined that contain _aegypti_ larvae; and the Breteau index, the
total number of containers with larvae of _aegypti_ per 100 houses.
All 3 are presented in the above report. I think the Breteau index
seems low in comparison with the house index. The statement that
dengue transmission is reduced if the indices quoted in the report
are below 1 percent is a little vague, as this usually refers to the
house index alone, and moreover this threshold is rather dubious for
some of the reasons given below on the use of these indices.
The value of such indices has been criticised because outbreaks of
diseases like dengue depend on many other factors such as the actual
numbers of larvae per container, the percentage that survive to
complete development and give rise to adults, and the population
density of humans.
Eradication campaigns in the 1940s and 1960s eliminated _Ae. aegypti_
from many Central and South American countries, including Paraguay,
but after such programs ceased in the early 1970s, _Ae. aegypti_
reappeared in most of those countries.
Another dengue vector, _Ae. albopictus_, originally from Asia, was
found in the 1980s and 1990s in some Latin American countries. It
has not been found in Paraguay, although it has been recorded in
Brazil ( in 1986) and Argentina (in 1998). - Mod.MS]
