[2] Ecuador
Date: 31 Jan 2006
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: El Comercio, Ecuador. Jan 31 2006 [trans. JGM; edited]
<http://www.elcomercio.com/noticia.asp?seccion=2&id=23571>

A 65-year-old woman who died last Sunday in Machala was diagnosed
with hemorrhagic dengue fever. The patient is the 2nd victim of this
outbreak in the current rainy season.
According to the Minister of Health, Dr. Ivan Zambrano, the patient
presented with the same features as another woman, who died 13 Jan
2006. Both patients were taken care of in Teofila Davila Hospital.
"The [65-year-old woman] was admitted last Friday [27 Jan]. Her
condition improved a little the next day, but on Sunday her condition
deteriorated, and she died. In both cases patients self-medicated
before being admitted".
According to Dr. Richard Molina, head of Teofilo Davila Hospital, the
patient was admitted to the emergency ward and later taken to the
Intensive Care Unit, where she stayed until she died. "She arrived
with an hemorrhagic condition and low platelets".
Additionally, in the aforementioned hospital there are 2 children
recovering from classic dengue fever, and a girl is still in critical
condition. "She is quite ill and she still is in the Hospital ICU."
According to Health Subsecretariat Statistics, until yesterday there
were 11 probable cases of classic dengue fever, 6 of them with
laboratory confirmation, 3 have a clinical diagnosis, and two died.
The provinces at risk are: Guayas, followed by El Oro and Manabi.
Probable cases of classic dengue fever until yesterday were 297; 231
from Guayas, 35 from El Oro, and 20 from Manabi.
Dr. Zambrano emphasized that the Crisis Committee is working
alongside province directors, the malaria program, and local
epidemiologists in order to report cases and to coordinate prevention actions.
Dr. Euclides Briones, Health Director from El Oro province, confirmed
that yesterday there was a meeting with parish groups and community
leaders, in order to coordinate actions and to prevent more deaths.
On the other hand, Guayas province Health Direction was at work last
weekend in the villages of Daule, El Triunfo, Playas, and Tenguel,
where there are plenty of cases.
According to Dr. Zambrano, these measures will continue throughout
the rainy season. He added that 500 persons were hired to work in the
National Malaria Eradication Service.
Last year [2005], 13 persons died from dengue hemorrhagic fever, most
of them from Guayas province.
