[3] Ecuador
Date: 26 Jan 2006
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: El Comercio, noticias, Ecuador. 26 Jan 2006 [trans. JGM; edited]
<http://www.elcomercio.com/noticia.asp?seccion=8&id=22688>

In San Francisco de Tenguel Hospital, relatives and neighbors meet
and greet each other many times a day. Many children and adults with
symptoms suggesting dengue fever, both classic and hemorrhagic forms,
are brought to this place, the only health center in Tenguel, Ecuador.
Tenguel is a remote parish belonging to Guayaquil province. It has
9600 inhabitants. Tenguel was brought to public attention after 13
Jan 2006, when the first victim of hemorrhagic dengue fever died in
the community of San Rafael.
Since then many persons have gone to the hospital seeking medical
care. Yesterday, a woman came from 12 de Junio street bringing her
5-year old son. "I am frightened, the boy has fever and he has a
nosebleed", she said, while she was placing the child in one of the
beds of the children's ward.
The boy was hospitalized for observation. Additionally, there is an
order from Health Authorities to perform examinations, and if a case
of hemorrhagic dengue fever is confirmed, then the person will be
immediately transported to Guayaquil in an ambulance.
A few steps away, and in the same 6-bed ward, a boy was recovering
from the severe illness. The boy was brought last Friday from San
Rafael, a village 6 kilometers away from the local road, where a girl
died because of hemorrhagic dengue fever. He is a schoolmate of the
deceased girl. His mother said that there are thousands of mosquitoes
in San Rafael.
In the women's ward there was a 5-year-old girl; a 25-year-old woman;
a 10-year-old girl; and a 5-year-old boy presented with symptoms
suggestive of dengue fever.
In the men's ward, a 36-year-old man was waiting for his wife to have
their daughter hospitalized. All members of this man's family became
sick with classic dengue fever. "First my wife, then my son and now
my daughter", the man said.
San Francisco Hospital has a 15-bed capacity. Yesterday, 6 persons
were admitted with the disease, and 7 additional patients were
waiting for the diagnosis to be confirmed. According to the Head of
the Hospital, Dr. Alfredo Arreaga, the outbreak is under control, but
the number of cases increased during the week 15-21 Jan 2006, when 41
cases of classic dengue fever and one case of dengue hemorrhagic
fever were reported. In the week from 21 Jan until now, 12 cases of
classic dengue fever and no cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever have
been reported.
"The order states that we do not maintain severely ill patients in
this place. This afternoon an ambulance from Guayaquil will arrive
for emergency cases. Yesterday (Tuesday, January 24), 3 children were
transported to Francisco de Ycaza Hospital for Sick Children,"
according to Dr. Arreaga.
While the Malaria program is performing fumigation and medicines are
awaited, the population is in on alert. In the community of San
Rafael, where the first focal cases where reported, 500 families
organized themselves. "There are no sewage systems, there is no tap
water, and puddles are everywhere. We are not taken care of. Here we
already have one deceased person and everybody is concerned about
Tenguel", said Marilu Ramirez, of the Local Improvement Committee.
"Streets in this community are not paved. You can smell the humidity,
not only because of heavy rainfalls last Tuesday, but also because of
the proximity of the Gala River. Here almost everybody has had fever.
[A woman] and her son, our neighbor, and my granddaughter are also at
the hospital," explained a resident.
This Saturday, Tenguel parish and its 7 communities will participate
in a cleaning campaign. Activities will be led by 20 community
leaders, health care workers from the Ministry of Health, members
from the Malaria Program, Policemen, and Firefighters. "We will clean
the village with the help of the community" pointed out Dr. Arreaga.
The National Service for Malaria Eradication (SNEM, according to its
Spanish initials) is fumigating and putting abate (a larvicide)
throughout Tenguel parish. Out of 60 households that underwent
abatization yesterday, 95 percent had water containers with mosquito larvae.
Tenguel parish is one of the 5 rural communities of Guayaquil
province. It has the 2nd largest number of inhabitants, after
Posorja, which has 18 447.
Next Saturday, a cleaning campaign will also be carried out in
Salitre, Daule, Santa Luc , and Tenguel, as announced by Public
Health Minister Dr. Ivan Zambrano.
--
